TECHNICAL GUIDE: USING ASSERTIONS IN PHP

Assertions are debugging tools used to verify your design assumptions during the
development phase in PHP.

They are easy to use, and PHP facilitates assert() and an assortment of
assert_options().

ASSERTION BASICS IN PHP

 1. Enabling and Disabling: Use the assert_options() method to activate and
    deactivate assertions, which is the default setting, and specify a custom
    error handler.

 2. Instantiating an Assertion: The assert() function is employed to devise an
    assertion. Its argument can be a string within backquotes or a lambda
    function.

 3. Custom Error Reporting: The developer can modify how assertion errors are
    broadcasted using ini_set() or specifying the third parameter in assert().
    If this third argument is for data, it will be provided to the custom
    handler.

ENABLING AND DISABLING ASSERTIONS

To alter the global assertion status, use the ini file or the ini_set() method.
The statement below deactivates assertions globally.

ini_set('assert.active', 0);


SPECIFYING AN ERROR MESSAGE

You can include a concise error message that will display when the assertion
fails. If an assertion stops, the script ends, and the message will not display.

Here's an example:

$value = -10;
assert('is_numeric($value)', 'The value is not numeric!');


CODE FROM THE INTERVIEW

Here is the php code:

// Ensure that PHP is in the development stage to display errors
if (ini_get('ASSERT_ACTIVE') != 1) {
    ini_set('ASSERT_ACTIVE', 1);
}

function validateAge(int $age): bool {
    return $age > 0;
}

// The assertion triggers an error if the condition is not met
assert(validateAge(-5), 'Age should be a positive value.');

Code Coverage is a metric to quantify how thoroughly your test suite evaluates
your source code. It's a critical tool for ensuring high test quality.


TOOLS FOR MEASURING CODE COVERAGE IN PHP

 1. PHPUnit: Cover strategy and observe the coverage via report generation.

 2. Xdebug: A powerful PHP extension that offers code coverage metrics and more.
    Its xdebug_start_code_coverage [https://xdebug.org/docs/code_coverage]
    function launches coverage tracking.

 3. PHPCOV: A command-line tool that processes code coverage data from PHP's
    Xdebug extension to produce a report in text or HTML format.


CODE COVERAGE EXAMPLE WORKFLOW WITH PHPUNIT

 1. First, make sure that you have installed PHPUnit:

    composer require --dev phpunit/phpunit


 2. Configure PHPUnit by creating a phpunit.xml file in your project's root:

    <phpunit>
        <logging>
            <log type="coverage-html" target="build/coverage" charset="UTF-8" yui="true" highlight="true" lowUpperBound="50" highLowerBound="80" />
        </logging>
    </phpunit>


 3. With the configuration set, run PHPUnit:

    vendor/bin/phpunit --coverage-html=build/coverage


 4. Review the report to gauge coverage by opening build/coverage/index.html in
    your browser.


PRACTICAL CODE COVERAGE TIPS

 * Aim to achieve at least 80% code coverage to ensure thorough testing.
 * Focus on critical and high-risk code segments.
 * Maintain coverage levels throughout the software development lifecycle,
   especially with iterations and code modifications.
 * Always distribute projects with complete tests and adequate coverage.


PHPUNIT CODE EXAMPLE

Here is the code:

// File: Calculator.php
class Calculator {
    public function add($a, $b) {
        return $a + $b;
    }

    public function subtract($a, $b) {
        return $a - $b;
    }
}

// File: CalculatorTest.php
use PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase;

require_once 'Calculator.php';

class CalculatorTest extends TestCase {
    public function testAdd() {
        $calc = new Calculator();
        $result = $calc->add(3, 5);
        $this->assertEquals(8, $result);
    }
}

// Run PHPUnit
# This is for demonstration purpose. Based on the path, command may vary
phpunit --coverage-html=build/coverage

