While PHP traditionally follows a stateless request/response model, WebSockets
enable full-duplex communication for more interactive web applications.

With WebSockets, a persistent connection is established, allowing the server to
send data to a client without the client first making a request. This real-time
responsiveness makes WebSockets ideal for applications like online gaming and
chat.


BENEFITS OF WEBSOCKETS IN PHP

 * Real-Time Messaging: Applications like messaging platforms can instantly
   deliver new messages to all connected clients.
 * Multiplayer Gaming: Supports real-time interactions, essential for real-time
   gaming experiences.
 * Live Feeds: Social media platforms use WebSockets to provide 'live' feeds to
   users without needing them to refresh the page.


PHP EXTENSIONS

 * Ratchet: A robust WebSocket library that simplifies WebSocket handling in
   PHP. It streamlines the process of creating both the server and client sides
   of the WebSocket.
 * PHP-WebSockets: A PHP script acting as a server, making it easy to experiment
   with WebSocket connections. However, it may lack the robustness and feature
   set of full-fledged libraries.


CODE EXAMPLE: INITIATING A WEBSOCKET CONNECTION

Here is the PHP and the JavaScript code:

PHP SERVER

use Ratchet\MessageComponentInterface;
use Ratchet\ConnectionInterface;

require_once 'vendor/autoload.php';

$loop = React\EventLoop\Factory::create();

$webSocketServer = new Ratchet\WebSocket\WsServer($app);
$webServer = new React\Socket\Server('127.0.0.1:8080', $loop);
$webServer = new Ratchet\Server\IoServer($webSocketServer, $webServer, $loop);

$loop->run();


CLIENT-SIDE JAVASCRIPT

const connection = new WebSocket('http://localhost:8080');
connection.onopen = () => {
  console.log('Connection established.');
  connection.send('Hello Server!');
};
connection.onmessage = (e) => {
  console.log('Received message: ', e.data);
};
connection.onerror = (error) => {
  console.error('WebSocket error: ', error);
};


Make sure the server is running and WebSocket library dependencies are
installed.

MVC (Model-View-Controller) is a software architectural pattern used to organize
code, especially in web applications. It helps in separating concerns, making
code more modular, easier to maintain and test.


MVC IN PHP

CODE STRUCTURE

MVC requires separating the application into three main components:

 * Model: Represents the core logical functionality and data.
 * View: Handles the visualization of Model data.
 * Controller: Acts as an interface between Model and View, directing the
   application's workflow.

Each component resides in its own folder:

root
|-- controllers
|-- models
|-- views
|-- config
|-- lib
|-- public
|   |-- css
|   |-- js
|   |-- images
|   |-- index.php
