 * models/: Contains classes responsible for data handling.
 * views/: Templates or files responsible for the application's user interface.
 * controllers/: Processes input and interact with the data before sending it to
   the View.

WORKFLOW

 1. User's Request: It all starts when the user interacts with the View by
    submitting a form or clicking links.
 2. Controller Action: The View routes the request based on interactions to a
    particular Controller.
 3. Model Interaction: The Controller, based on the request, interacts with the
    associated Model to process or retrieve necessary data.
 4. Display Data: The processed data from the Model is then sent to the
    appropriate View for rendering.

CODE EXAMPLE: INDEX.PHP

This setup utilizes Composer for autoloading all classes, minimizing manual
class inclusions.

<?php
require 'config.php';
require 'autoloader.php';

use Core\Router;

$router = new Router();
$router->route();


CLASS AUTOLOADING

Composer provides efficient and uniform class loading. After running composer
install, it generates a vendor/autoload.php file that is referenced within your
index.php.

 * composer.json:

   {
       "autoload": {
           "psr-4": {
               "Core\\": "core/",
               "App\\": "app/"
           }
       }
   }


ROUTING

The Router class parses URLs and determines which Controller and method should
handle the request.

 * core/Router.php:

   <?php
   namespace Core;

   class Router {
       public function route() {
           $url = $_SERVER['REQUEST_URI'];
           // Perform routing based on $url...
       }
   }


CODE EXAMPLE: USERCONTROLLER.PHP

The Controller is responsible for taking user input (e.g., from forms) and
feeding it to the appropriate Model for further processing.

 * controllers/UserController.php:

   <?php
   namespace App\Controllers;

   class UserController {
       public function register() {
           $userModel = new UserModel();
           $userData = $this->validateAndSanitize($_POST);
           if($userModel->save($userData)) {
               $this->redirect('/success');
           } else {
               $this->redirect('/error');
           }
       }
   }


CODE EXAMPLE: USERMODEL.PHP

The Model is the home of your application's domain logic and data manipulation.

 * models/UserModel.php:

   <?php
   namespace App\Models;

   class UserModel {
       public function save($data) {
           // Save data to DB or other storage
           return true;
       }
   }


VIEW RENDERING

The View often uses a template system that dynamically replaces placeholders
with relevant data.

 * views/user/registrationForm.php:

   <form method="post">
       <!-- Form fields -->
       <button type="submit">Register</button>
   </form>


The register method in the UserController uses PHP's require statement to
include the View while having the necessary data accessible.

CODE EXAMPLE: USERCONTROLLER.PHP

 * UserController.php:

   public function register() {
       // ...
       $userData = $this->validateAndSanitize($_POST);
       require 'views/user/registrationForm.php';
       // ...
   }



ADDITIONAL FRAMEWORKS

While raw PHP is a great starting point for understanding fundamental MVC
concepts and design principles, for real-world production applications, it might
be more practical to use a PHP framework such as Laravel, Symfony, CodeIgniter
or CakePHP. These frameworks offer streamlined MVC implementations, built-in
libraries, and components for web development, especially repetitious tasks like
routing, database interactions, and view rendering.

Laravel, like many modern PHP frameworks, employs an event-driven architecture
through its convenient event system.

CORE COMPONENTS

 1. Event Classes: These are "carrier" classes that bundle and deliver event
    data. Each class represents a different event type.

 2. Listeners: They specifically handle events and take appropriate actions when
    events are fired. All listeners are registered with events that they want to
    "listen" to.

 3. Event Dispatcher: The central hub that coordinates and dispatches events to
    their respective listeners. It's the heart of Laravel's event system.

 4. Subscribers: These are higher-level listeners capable of listening to
    multiple events.

 5. Event Providers (Laravel Terminology): Providers are responsible for setting
    up event and listener relationships. They define the events each listener
    should handle. Providers are a standard part of Laravel's service container.

EVENT FLOW

 1. Event Triggering: Events are usually triggered within business logic code.
    This is typically done using one of Laravel's helper methods.

 2. Event Bubbling: After an event is fired, it moves up through the application
    in an "event bubble." During this time, any registered subscribers or
    listeners can respond to the event.

 3. Listener Response: Once registered, event listeners carry out their
    designated actions when an event goes through its lifecycle.

PRACTICAL EXAMPLE

Consider an online store that triggers an event every time a customer places an
order. In this case, once the event is fired, the system may send an email to
the customer, update inventory, and generate an invoice.

CODE EXAMPLE: DEFINING AN EVENT

Here is the Laravel code:

namespace App\Events;

use App\Models\Order;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Events\Dispatchable;
use Illuminate\Queue\SerializesModels;

class OrderPlaced
{
    use Dispatchable, SerializesModels;

    public $order;

    public function __construct(Order $order)
    {
        $this->order = $order;
    }
}


In this example, OrderPlaced is an event class, and it carries the order that
was placed.

CODE EXAMPLE: FIRING AN EVENT

use App\Events\OrderPlaced;
use App\Models\Order;

$order = Order::find(1);

OrderPlaced::dispatch($order);


CODE EXAMPLE: EVENT LISTENER

namespace App\Listeners;

use App\Events\OrderPlaced;

class SendOrderConfirmation
{
    public function handle(OrderPlaced $event)
    {
        // Code to send confirmation email
    }

    public function subscribe($events)
    {
        $events->listen(
            'App\Events\OrderPlaced',
            'App\Listeners\SendOrderConfirmation@handle'
        );
    }
}
